<br>
Alleys were rank from the fecal waste that flowed through their centers until they met culverts to the river below, eventually flushing out to the Ocean of Tears.<br>
<br>
Neriak was a dangerous place, despite the guards that patrolled most of it.  But, once one left the common areas of the Foreign Quarters, and took the ramps that lead to the housing districts, it became something entirely worse.<br>
<br>
City guards did not patrol this place, Nobles did not come here to slum.  It was the home to Ogres and Trolls, and the odd Human or Erudite.<br>
<br>
What passed for security in this wretched cave?  Troll mercenaries, Ogre gangsters.  Their hands eagerly extended to accept bribes, or lay a beating upon you that would end your life.<br>
<br>
Justice was bought and sold here as easily as brothel slaves.  One could acquire anything one wanted here.  The blind eyes of the City Officials, combined with the bought arms of justice made this a smugglers paradise.<br>
<br>
Assassins, smugglers, cutthroats, slave traders, murderers, thieves, fugitives, and mercenaries inhabited this place.  Rough hewn buildings in seeming decay opened up to reveal lavishly appointed and comfortably furnished rooms and apartments.  Smuggling, slave trading, assassination and general skullduggery were profitable if one was competent and knew his place.<br>
<br>
Without question this place had its Lord.  Varger, an Erudian Knight, had his hand deep into the pockets of just about every illicit trade that operated here.  He used well his diplomatic immunity as Ambassador from Paineel.  He also used well his heavy coin purse, and knew exactly who to pay to keep this part of town exactly the way it was.<br>
<br>
Varger prevented open crime with a vengeance.  One had to operate in stealth to survive here, or one was readily dispatched.<br>
<br>
Varger kept the Foreign Quarter quiet, and off of the Itineraries  of Neriak’s Council.  Varger made sure the guards were of his choosing.  Varger made sure everyone kept their place.  Varger decided who could operate in what territories and who could move in and take those territories away.<br>
<br>
If you wanted to wage war against a competing thieves guild, you asked Varger.  If you wanted to assassinate a citizen of Neriak, you checked with Varger.<br>
<br>
Nothing was done without Varger’s consent, unless you had a death wish.<br>
<br>
Varger liked to make examples of his enemies.  He liked to raise them as skeletal servants and parade them quietly down the streets of the Quarter.<br>
<br>
Nobody crossed Varger and lived.  Nobody had done so in the ten years since he took control.  Likely nobody would do so while he lived.  He was perhaps the one resident of this place that would die of old age.<br>
<br>
To Mantros, Varger was a God.<br>
<br>
Varger never spoke.  Or at least, none had reported hearing him do so.  Only his closest advisors knew for sure.  Varger did not need to speak.  His eyes told you all you needed to know.<br>
<br>
Mantros had come to the Quarter because he simply had nowhere else to go.<br>
<br>
Selling the silver buckles from his clothing, he managed to afford a room in the Quarter.<br>
<br>
It was not long before his money ran out, and his luck with it.<br>
<br>
He was tossed out, literally, into the alley… and with a splash in the septic waters he landed.  Brown and smelly water sprayed about and coated him in filth.  Unfortunately for the Troll Landlord, it also coated Varger as he roamed past unheard.<br>
<br>
As Varger turned to end the Troll’s life, Mantros fled.  He did not get far when darkness engulfed him and he could barely walk, and barely see.<br>
<br>
Skeletal fingers grab his arms and lifted him.  He was carried before Varger.<br>
<br>
Varger looked directly into the eyes of Mantros.<br>
<br>
Mantros looked into the eyes of death.<br>
<br>
