<br>
That he was aboard ship was certain.  He could feel the gentle sway of a barque navigating calmer waters.<br>
<br>
What did Varger plan for him… the last thing he remembered was being stretched before him, his limbs held be skeletal servants, as Varger weaved a spell and put him into a death like sleep.<br>
<br>
His fingers roamed about the interior of his confine, seeking a flaw in the wood to work away at. Finding none, he begin to pound at the lid.  Using only mild strength at first to see if he would draw attention, then growing bolder, and hitting harder.<br>
<br>
The lid would not budge.<br>
<br>
It was humid, sticky and hot.  And after many hours, Mantros passed out exhausted.  He awoke some time later coughing.  His small prison had filled with smoke, and he could hear the clash of metal nearby.  Unknown to him, the Captain and Crew had been boarded by pirates, and the ship now foundered, burning and slowly sinking, as the crew fought for their lives.<br>
<br>
The smoke was all the information Mantros needed however.  He would escape now or die.  Pounding his fists bloody at the lid, it finally began to give, and eventually the hinges popped free of the wood, and Mantros exploded forth from the coffin and dived sideways to assess his situation.<br>
<br>
Peeking over the top of a crate, he took in the scene.  He was in the belly of a ship, and 3 cutthroats had cornered an officer.  The man fought with skill but would soon be overcome.  Mantros turned and caught a glimpse of sunlight, and the stairs to the deck.  Without hesitation he ran through the smoky interior and rushed up the stairs.<br>
<br>
The two vessels were locked together with grapple and rope.  The cutthroats busy, working rapidly to sever the ties that bound them to the burning ship.  Nearby he could see land.  Forest and beach barely visible in the bright daylight.  He gathered breath and jumped over the railing, head first into the sea below.<br>
<br>
Head first into the mast that had burned away, and now lay smoking in the water beside the ship.  In his haste, he had been careless, and pain blinded him as his eye was torn from his socket, spilling red into the waters.<br>
<br>
He lay floating on his back, face covered in blood, his head reeling from the blow, and barely conscious.<br>
<br>
As his mind cleared, he tore at his shirt and covered the wound with a makeshift bandage.  The pain from the salt water entering the wound was unbearable.   His hand tight over his eye socket, he swam, and kicked his way to shore.<br>
